\cf2 \ul \ulc2 Cyclic association:\ulnone \'a0While not discussed above or demonstrated in the test code, all of the Protectors can quit, just as our Warriors were able to do previously.\
\ul Separate compilation and namespaces:\ulnone \'a0Again, use separate compilation. You may, if you like, put all of the Protector types in one header / implementation pair, and the various Noble types in another pair. Or create a header / implementation pair for every class, as you like. Place all classes in the WarriorCraft namespace.\
\ul Framework:\ulnone \'a0While we see that the different Nobles battle somewhat differently, really they are doing the same sequence of things, involving 1) determining their own strength, 2) either defending themselves or having their army defend them, and 3) winning or losing with the corresponding adjustment to their strength, and in the case of the Lords, the strengths of each of their Protectors. This is why we only need on battle method in the base class Noble as it can call on methods in the derived Noble classes to correctly handle each stage.\
